\newpage
\setcounter{tocdepth}{3} % Go 3 levels deep for ToC items

\begin{document}

\chapter{Introduction}
\section{Background}
Some introductory content...

\subsection{Motivation}
Additional content...

\section{Methods}
\subsection{Experimental Setup}
\begin{description}
  \item[Hardware:]...
  \item[Software:]...
\end{description}

\chapter{Results}
\section{Findings}
\begin{figure}
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.8\linewidth]{example_figure}
  \caption{Example Figure Caption}
  \label{fig:example_figure}
\end{figure}

\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{List of Figures} % Manually add Section for LoF
\listoffigures
\newpage

\begin{table}
  \centering
  \begin{tblr}{colspec={lX}, width=0.8\linewidth}
    \textbf{Item 1} & Details
    \textbf{Item 2} & Details
  \end{tblr}
  \caption{Example Table Caption}
  \label{tab:example_table}
\end{table}

\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{List of Tables} % Manually add Section for LoT
\listoftables

\section{Discussion}
Some discussion content...

\end{document}

```

Here's the breakdown:

1. The `\tableofcontents*` command generates an automatic Table of Contents with the current depth of chapters/sections/subsections.
2. The `\setcounter{tocdepth}{3}` command sets the maximum depth of the ToC to show chapter-level, section-level, and subsection-level items.
3. The `\addcontentsline` commands manually add a section for the List of Figures (LoF) and List of Tables (LoT) to the ToC.
4. Hyperref and package options ensure the ToC is clickable and well-styled.
5. `titlesec` package ensures consistent section formatting.

Remember, you can adjust the `tocdepth` and add/remove sections as per your document's needs. The automatic generating part is handled by LaTeX itself; you merely structure your document, and LaTeX creates the ToC accordingly.

